    {
      id: 'g1',
      title: 'Word Order: OVS (Object-Verb-Subject)',
      body: 'Klingon is one of the rare OVS languages on Earth (or off it). "The commander found the spy" → ghoqwI\' Sam la\' ("spy find commander"). Adverbs go first; prepositional phrases go before the object. This is the opposite of English SVO order.'
    },
    {
      id: 'g2',
      title: 'Verb Prefixes Encode Subject AND Object',
      body: 'A single prefix covers both who acts and who is acted upon. jI- = I (no object); vI- = I...it; bI- = you (no object); Da- = you...it; Ø- = he/she (no object); lu- = they...it. The prefix must appear even when nouns are stated explicitly.'
    },
    {
      id: 'g3',
      title: 'No Copula  -  Adjectives Are Verbs',
      body: 'Klingon has no verb "to be." Adjectives function as stative verbs: "tlhIngan jIH" = "Klingon, I am." "batlh jIH" = "I am honorable." This makes Klingon feel structurally very different from Indo-European languages.'
    },
    {
      id: 'g4',
      title: 'Three Noun Classes for Plurals',
      body: 'Three plural suffixes based on noun class: -pu\' for beings capable of language (SuvwI\'pu\' = warriors); -Du\' for body parts (ghopDu\' = hands); -mey for everything else (quSmey = chairs). Using -mey for a being implies they are scattered randomly  -  considered insulting.'
    },
    {
      id: 'g5',
      title: 'Five Ordered Noun Suffix Types',
      body: 'Noun suffixes must appear in strict type order: (1) size/endearment (-\'a\' big, -Hom small, -oy dear); (2) number (-pu\'/-Du\'/-mey); (3) qualification (-qoq so-called, -na\' true/definite); (4) possession (-wIj my, -lIj your, -Daj his/her, -chaj their); (5) syntactic (-Daq at/in, -vo\' from, -vad for/to, -\'e\' topic).'
    },
    {
      id: 'g6',
      title: 'Verb Aspect  -  Not Tense',
      body: 'Klingon marks grammatical aspect, not tense. Time is shown by adverbs or context. The aspect suffixes: -pu\' = perfective (done); -ta\' = accomplished intentionally; -taH = continuous/ongoing; -lI\' = in progress toward a goal. Example: jISoppu\' = "I have eaten"; jISoptaH = "I am eating (continuously)."'
    },
    {
      id: 'g7',
      title: 'Imperative Prefixes',
      body: 'Commands use special imperative prefixes: yI- = command with one object; pe- = plural subject command; HI- = do it to me!; gho- = do it to us!; tI- = do it to them! yIHaD = "Study!" (imperative). yIqIm = "Pay attention!" A well-known example: yIHaD! DaH! = "Study! Now!"'
    },
    {
      id: 'g8',
      title: 'Sentences as Objects: \'e\'',
      body: 'To embed a full sentence as the object of another verb, place \'e\' after the first sentence: "bIpIv \'e\' vItu\'" = "I observe that you are healthy." The word \'e\' is treated as a 3rd-person singular object pronoun representing the entire preceding sentence.'
    }
